body:
oh thanks for the investigation! it doesn't affect only linux, but it's more visible on Linux because the clocks are less precise probably

with the modified example:
```
use std::time::Duration;

use bevy::app::ScheduleRunnerPlugin;
use bevy::prelude::*;
use bevy::time::common_conditions::on_timer;

fn main() {
    App::new()
        .add_plugins((
            DefaultPlugins.set(ScheduleRunnerPlugin::run_loop(Duration::from_secs_f64(
                1.0 / 60.0,
            ))),
        ))
        .add_systems(Update, (inc, tick.run_if(on_timer(Duration::from_secs(1)))))
        .insert_resource(Counter(0))
        .run();
}

#[derive(Resource)]
struct Counter(u32);

fn tick(time: Res<Time>, mut counter: ResMut<Counter>) {
    let t = std::time::SystemTime::now()
        .duration_since(std::time::SystemTime::UNIX_EPOCH)
        .unwrap();
    println!(
        "{t:?}: elapsed: {:?} ({})",
        time.elapsed_secs_f64(),
        counter.0
    );
    counter.0 = 0;
}

fn inc(mut counter: ResMut<Counter>) {
    counter.0 += 1;
}
```

I have the following log:
```
1743354702.258232s: elapsed: 1.000008125 (53153)
1743354703.258235s: elapsed: 2.000014309 (54740)
1743354704.258239s: elapsed: 3.000028101 (54573)
1743354705.258223s: elapsed: 4.000016726 (54477)
1743354706.258219s: elapsed: 5.000018601 (54302)
1743354707.258199s: elapsed: 6.000002958 (54100)
1743354708.258198s: elapsed: 7.00000925 (54270)
```

So macOS is also affected. The clock is still precise, but the systems run as fast as possible, the duration on the `ScheduleRunnerPlugin` is not respected

@bushrat011899 any idea?

`sleep` is something that is provided by the platform, there is no general `no_std` replacement.

we could gate `run_loop` on `std`, or make it require a `sleep` function on `no_std`?
